===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|hamer}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hamor}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hamaraz}} (compare {{cog|fy|hammer}}, {{cog|nds|Hamer}}, {{cog|nl|hamer}}, {{cog|de|Hammer}}, {{cog|da|hammer}}, {{cog|sv|hammare}}).
The Germanic ''*hamaraz'' "tool with a stone head" derives from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*h₂eḱmoros}} (compare {{cog|sa|अश्मर|tr=aśmará||stony}}), itself a derivation from {{m|ine-pro|*h₂éḱmō||stone}}.

For {{m|ine-pro|*h₂éḱmō||stone}}, compare {{cog|lt|akmuõ}}, {{cog|ru|камень}}, {{cog|sh|kamēn}}, {{cog|sq|kmesë||sickle}}, {{cog|grc|ἄκμων||meteor rock, anvil}}, {{cog|ae|𐬥𐬀𐬨𐬯𐬀|tr=asman}}, {{cog|sa|अश्मन्|tr=áśman|sc=Deva}}) (root {{m|ine-pro|*h₂eḱ-||sharp}}).

